         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W. ¶ Decr 19/67 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I am very glad to hear of your trip to King George's Sound I hope you will have derived enjoyment as well as health from it. ¶  ¶ I think I repor...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">67.12.19</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Decr 19/67</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am very glad to hear of your trip to King George's Sound I hope you will have derived enjoyment as well as health from it.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I think I reported in my last the arrival of the <name key="Epacrideae">Epacrideae</name> etc pr Sussex and pr Great Britain and I have just attacked that Order.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>G. Bentham to M, 17 November 1867.</p>
               </note> The <name key="Goodenovieae">Goodenovieae</name> have taken me longer than I expected having had to analyse the ovarium of every species and often of many specimens. I find in Dampiera great and constant differences in the ovulum which make good sections combined with inflorescence. I fear however I must make a genus (<name key="Verreauxia">Verreauxia</name>) of D. Reinwardtii and D. Verreauxii which have not the characteristic flowers of Dampiera and yet will neither go into Scaevola nor Goodenia — De Vriese's genera are <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">all</hi>
               </seg> as bad as the rest of his work.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Euthales">Euthales</name> must evidently go back to <name key="Velleia">Velleia</name> where Labillardière put it. The calyx tube is always quite free whilst the corolla is adnate In <name key="Goodenia%20barbata">Goodenia barbata</name> etc the calyx tube is exceedingly short but adnate and the lobes are adnate some way up. <name key="Euthales">Euthales</name> has also the inflorescence of <name key="Velleya">Velleya</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Velleya">Velleya</name>
                     </seg> is an orthographic variant of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Velleia">Velleia</name>
                     </seg>.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I shall carefully go through your observations on <name key="Epacrideae">Epacrideae</name>. I do not like suppressing a genus so universally adopted as <name key="Leucopogon">Leucopogon</name> — and if it is retained as a section and proves at all a natural one I cannot but think it better to leave it as a genus — there is a great difference between making a genus and keeping up one already made. If it can be done with propriety I shall have the less scruple in doing so as I see you have provided for it by keeping up the section and by naming all your new species as <name key="Leucopogon">Leucopogon</name>s as well as as<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">word repeated in MS.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <name key="Styphelias">Styphelias</name>. The evil of the double synonymy is thus already created and whether a group be a section or genus is in many cases purely arbitrary — and in matter of doubt botanists at large would rather follow Brown than any of us.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="">Robert Brown (1773-1858). </seg>See Lucas (2003), pp. 269–72.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As I said before I hope to begin printing at the end of Feby so as to get the volume out before I leave town in summer. You would much oblige me by sending the remaining <name key="Monopetalae">Monopetalae</name> — I am having the <name key="Stylideae">Stylideae</name>
               <name key="Campanulaceae">Campanulaceae</name> &amp; <name key="Goodenovieae">Goodenovieae</name> packed up and shall send them off I hope in a few days They are in excellent condition The mould I mentioned as having appeared on one apparently rather fresh specimen only extended to 3 or 4 sheets and appears to have been got rid of by changing the paper<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>G. Bentham to M, 19 October 1867.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dr F. Mueller FRS</p>
